	<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-7865">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/df3ec5506ba59d2ed3b951b7057e97d0?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/df3ec5506ba59d2ed3b951b7057e97d0?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://dcid.me" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Daniel Cid</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-09-01T12:56:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2016/09/iot-home-router-botnet-leveraged-in-large-ddos-attack.html#comment-7865">September 1, 2016</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>We actually debated internally if we should call them IoT or not, since they are just routers. </p>
<p>We ended up agreeing to IoT because they are part of the multitude of devices people have at their homes and are generally forgotten, unmanaged and unprotected. It includes cameras, watches, routers, etc, etc. That matches the wikipedia terminology:</p>
<p>&#8220;The internet of things (IoT) is the network of physical devices, vehicles, buildings and other items—embedded with electronics, software, sensors, actuators, and network connectivity that enable these objects to collect and exchange data.&#8221;</p>
<p>thanks!</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment even depth-3" id="comment-7866">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/7b4fe6ac48588517a16b089ae483957f?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/7b4fe6ac48588517a16b089ae483957f?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name">Edward Dore</span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-09-01T13:12:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2016/09/iot-home-router-botnet-leveraged-in-large-ddos-attack.html#comment-7866">September 1, 2016</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Hmmm, interesting viewpoint.</p>
<p>I always think of IoT devices as embedded systems that are doing something (collecting data via sensors etc.) and working together in order to achieve specific tasks, whereas a router (or switch or access point etc.) is just an incidental network device that only serves to connect other network devices.</p>
<p>However, much like &#8220;cloud&#8221;, &#8220;IoT&#8221; is an overused, vaguely defined marketing term which can be applied to pretty much anything that&#8217;s got some form of network connectivity.<br />
For example, is a network connected printer an &#8220;IoT&#8221; device, or is it just a printer?</p>
<p>In the case of the printer, you send it something from a computer and it prints it, whereas more classic IoT devices (thermostats etc.) generally need a collection of different devices which work together in order to accomplish something.<br />
The printer also takes direct human input (the file to print) and translates it to a physical output, whereas a lot of IoT is normally about M2M communication and human involvement is pretty limited and infrequent (setting a temperature on a thermostat for example).</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment odd alt depth-4" id="comment-7868">
